<h2 id="deliverability-reality">📬 Deliverability: The Real Numbers</h2>

I ran deliverability tests across our venue network using seed lists. AWeber hit 93.4% inbox placement across Gmail, Outlook, and Yahoo in January 2026.

That's solid but not exceptional. For context, Klaviyo hit 96.2% and Mailchimp hit 91.8% in the same tests.

AWeber's deliverability holds up because they're strict about list hygiene. They'll suspend accounts with high bounce rates quickly. This protects their IP reputation — and yours.

One issue: if you're importing subscribers from a WiFi captive portal (like many of our clients do), expect AWeber to scrutinize your list. Have your data collection consent documentation ready. They asked for it twice during our setup.

<h2 id="final-verdict">🏁 Final Verdict</h2>

AWeber in 2026 is a reliable, simple email platform that works best for operators who don't need complexity. It's not trying to be Klaviyo or HubSpot. It's trying to be the email tool that single-location business owners actually use.

For that use case, it delivers. The interface stays out of your way. Emails get delivered. Support answers the phone.

The multi-location limitations are real and won't be solved by workarounds at scale. If you're operating 5+ venues and need location-specific campaigns, look elsewhere first.

For everyone else — especially operators who've bounced off "more powerful" tools because they couldn't figure them out — AWeber deserves serious consideration.

My recommendation: Start with the free plan. Send 500 emails. See if the interface clicks for you. That'll tell you more than any review.

